An important result for IPSL-CM5 is the very strong difference between the climate sensitivities obtained with IPSL-CM5A-LR and IPSL-CM5B-LR. While the climate sensitivity of IPSL-CM5A-LR (\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\Updelta T^e_s(2\hbox{CO}_2) \approx 4.1K$$\end{document}) lies in the upper part of the sensitivity range of the CMIP3 models, the sensitivity of IPSL-CM5B-LR (\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\Updelta T^e_s(2\hbox{CO}_2) \approx 2.6K$$\end{document}) falls in the lower part (Meehl et al. 2007b). The analysis of the reasons for these differences requires further work.
